  "prompt": "The bond angle of Sulphur dioxide is greater than that of Ozone. Why?",
  "response": "The bond angle in molecules is influenced by several factors, including the molecular geometry and the presence of lone pairs of electrons.\n\n1. **Molecular Geometry**:\n   - Sulfur dioxide (SO\u2082) has a bent molecular geometry due to the presence of one lone pair of electrons on the sulfur atom. The bond angle in SO\u2082 is approximately 120 degrees.\n   - Ozone (O\u2083), on the other hand, has a bent shape as well, but with a smaller bond angle of approximately 117 degrees, due to the presence of one lone pair on each of the outer oxygen atoms.\n\n2. **Lone Pair Repulsion**:\n   - In SO\u2082, the lone pair on sulfur exerts repulsive forces that push the bonding pairs of electrons slightly away from each other, but since SO\u2082 has only one lone pair affecting the bond between sulfur and the oxygen atoms, the bond angle can be larger than that in ozone.\n   - In contrast, in ozone, the pair of lone pairs on both outer oxygen atoms leads to greater repulsion, which reduces the bond angle further. The bond angles are compressed more than in SO\u2082 due to the cumulative effects of lone pairs.\n\n3. **Hybridization**:\n   - Sulfur in SO\u2082 undergoes sp\u00b2 hybridization, allowing for a more planar structure which tends to have larger bond angles.\n   - Ozone has a resonance structure that does not favor any single hybridization model, but the effective hybridization can be considered similar to that of a resonance hybrid with some contribution from an sp\u00b2 character, albeit constrained more by lone pairs waiting on the terminal oxygen atoms.\n\nIn conclusion, the bond angle in sulfur dioxide is greater than that in ozone primarily due to the geometry of the molecules and the influence of lone pair repulsions, which are more pronounced in ozone.",
